1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:02,720
If you're preparing for a data scientist interview,

2

00:00:02,720  -->  00:00:05,180
here's a question you need to be ready to answer.

3

00:00:05,180  -->  00:00:07,560
If you're building a linear regression model with

4

00:00:07,560  -->  00:00:10,680
a single independent variable and an intercept,

5

00:00:10,680  -->  00:00:13,080
how many coefficients are you calculating?

6

00:00:13,080  -->  00:00:15,140
In order to answer this question,

7

00:00:15,140  -->  00:00:19,520
we have one independent variable which would have a coefficient attached to it,

8

00:00:19,520  -->  00:00:21,460
and you'd also have an intercept

9

00:00:21,460  -->  00:00:24,320
that doesn't have any independent variables attached to it.

10

00:00:24,320  -->  00:00:27,870
You would have two coefficients in this linear model.

11

00:00:27,870  -->  00:00:31,400
One of the coefficients would tell you how that independent variable

12

00:00:31,400  -->  00:00:35,925
affects another the response variable of your model.

13

00:00:35,925  -->  00:00:40,140
Then the intercept is this placeholder of where it would start.

14

00:00:40,140  -->  00:00:43,140
You can imagine drawing this line.

15

00:00:43,140  -->  00:00:45,180
The intercept is where the line starts,

16

00:00:45,180  -->  00:00:48,085
and then the slope of this line is the other coefficient,

17

00:00:48,085  -->  00:00:53,375
and along the x-axis is this independent variable that you're looking at.

18

00:00:53,375  -->  00:00:55,890
Then along the y-axis is your response variable.

19

00:00:55,890  -->  00:01:01,350
That's you want to relate age and height,

20

00:01:01,350  -->  00:01:04,750
and you could have age on the x-axis,

21

00:01:04,940  -->  00:01:07,545
height on the y-axis.

22

00:01:07,545  -->  00:01:14,530
The most common height as the starting point and then for each year older,

23

00:01:14,530  -->  00:01:17,630
how much taller do you get is the slope of this line,

24

00:01:17,630  -->  00:01:19,080
and that's the other coefficient.

25

00:01:19,080  -->  00:01:21,365
Where the line starts, the slope of the line.

26

00:01:21,365  -->  00:01:23,370
Those are the two coefficients in the model.

27

00:01:23,370  -->  00:01:25,810
Another question you'd want to be prepared for if

28

00:01:25,810  -->  00:01:28,630
you're interviewing for a data scientist interview is,

29

00:01:28,630  -->  00:01:33,405
does logistic regression predict a categorical target or numeric target?

30

00:01:33,405  -->  00:01:38,650
The way that you answer this question is that it predicts a categorical target.

31

00:01:38,650  -->  00:01:43,430
Logistic regression is aimed at predicting usually (1, 0) outcomes.

32

00:01:43,430  -->  00:01:46,735
Yes, no outcomes. Did you make it or not?

33

00:01:46,735  -->  00:01:50,190
But basically, these binary categories.

34

00:01:50,190  -->  00:01:54,200
Linear regression is used for quantitative outcomes.

35

00:01:54,200  -->  00:01:57,430
Which part of a linear regression result tells you whether

36

00:01:57,430  -->  00:02:04,120
an independent variable is a statistically significant impact on the dependent variable.

37

00:02:04,120  -->  00:02:06,705
In this case, this is the p-value,

38

00:02:06,705  -->  00:02:10,050
and it's the p-value associated with that specific coefficient.

39

00:02:10,050  -->  00:02:11,830
In a linear model,

40

00:02:11,830  -->  00:02:16,005
you basically get all of your coefficients and a p-value attached to them.

41

00:02:16,005  -->  00:02:18,550
Each of those p-values tells you if

42

00:02:18,550  -->  00:02:20,390
that specific independent variable is

43

00:02:20,390  -->  00:02:22,960
related to your response or your dependent variable.

44

00:02:22,960  -->  00:02:26,270
Usually, we use a threshold like (0,

45

00:02:26,270  -->  00:02:28,260
5), and if your p-value is less than that,

46

00:02:28,260  -->  00:02:31,540
then that suggests that that particular variable

47

00:02:31,540  -->  00:02:37,060
is responsible for a statistically significant impact on the response.

48

00:02:37,060  -->  00:02:40,320
Which part of a linear regression result tells you whether

49

00:02:40,320  -->  00:02:45,905
an independent variable has a practically significant impact on the dependent variable?

50

00:02:45,905  -->  00:02:48,960
Practical dependence is usually related to

51

00:02:48,960  -->  00:02:52,860
how high the impact is or how much the impact is on the response.

52

00:02:52,860  -->  00:02:56,165
In these cases, it would be the coefficient themselves.

53

00:02:56,165  -->  00:02:59,620
The p-value is the statistically significant.

54

00:02:59,620  -->  00:03:02,040
But then let's say,

55

00:03:02,040  -->  00:03:07,440
you want to know if you're developing a drug to make people live longer,

56

00:03:07,440  -->  00:03:13,020
but it makes you live statistically significant longer by 37 seconds.

57

00:03:13,020  -->  00:03:16,030
Well, that's statistically significant,

58

00:03:16,030  -->  00:03:18,670
but it's not very practically significant and not going

59

00:03:18,670  -->  00:03:21,835
to be able to do anything in those 37 seconds.

60

00:03:21,835  -->  00:03:26,950
That's probably more meaningful than that you couldn't have done in the earlier parts.

61

00:03:26,950  -->  00:03:30,670
But practical significance might say, Oh,

62

00:03:30,670  -->  00:03:33,330
does it let me live 20 years or three year,

63

00:03:33,330  -->  00:03:34,530
or 20 more years,

64

00:03:34,530  -->  00:03:40,005
or 30 more days or depending on your situation.

65

00:03:40,005  -->  00:03:43,170
But in any case, the practical significance

66

00:03:43,170  -->  00:03:47,230
here is associated with the coefficient in the model.
